                            <div class="card-body">
                                <p class="card-text">During your search process, the two most common interviews you will
                                    face are Coding (Technical) Interviews and Behavioral Interviews</p>
                                <h4 class="card-title">Coding Interviews</h4>

                                <p class="card-text">Preparing for Coding Interviews is as simple as daily practice.
                                    Coding interviews will consist of questions where you are asked to write a program
                                    that will do what the instructions say to do. You can ususually pick the language of
                                    your choice, but as the material never exceeds the level of your Data Structures
                                    (CSCI 121) or Algorithms Course (CSCI 160), you probably will be most comfortable
                                    using the language you used in those courses (Java, Python, etc)</p>
                                <p class="card-text"><a href="https://www.leetcode.com" target="_blank">Leetcode</a> is
                                    a website with thousands of practice coding interview problems</p>
                                <p class="card-text">Rather than attempting to solve every problem on Leetcode though, I
                                    would follow some sort of study order, <a
                                        href="https://yangshun.github.io/tech-interview-handbook/algorithms/algorithms-introduction/"
                                        target="_blank">like this</a>, which links to Leetcode problems but in a
                                    well-defined progression of problem topics (Arrays, Lists, etc) </p>

                                <h4 class="card-title">Behavioral Interviews</h4>
                                <p class="card-text">These are questions like, "Tell me about a time when you had a
                                    problem with a team member", etc. Check out <a
                                        href="https://www.themuse.com/advice/30-behavioral-interview-questions-you-should-be-ready-to-answer"
                                        target="_blank">this question list</a> and utilize the <a
                                        href="https://www.themuse.com/advice/star-interview-method" target="_blank">STAR
                                        behavioral interview method</a> to answer them</p>
                                <h4 class="card-title">**Never go into any interview (even pre-recorded interviews, like
                                    HireVues, without researching the company and why you want to work there/how you
                                    measure up to the job description (really study that thing, Google what you don't
                                    know)**</h4>

